#compdef svelte-kit
# =============================================================================
# svelte-kit — Svelte team's "web development, streamlined" — the
#               binary shipped by `@sveltejs/kit` that synchronizes
#               generated type definitions for SvelteKit projects.
#               In the modern SvelteKit workflow (SvelteKit 2+),
#               most user-facing operations (dev server, build,
#               preview) flow through Vite (`vite dev`, `vite
#               build`, `vite preview`).  The `svelte-kit`
#               binary specifically handles the one thing Vite
#               cannot: TYPE-GENERATION FOR THE GENERATED ROUTE-
#               LEVEL `$types.d.ts` FILES that SvelteKit creates
#               based on a project's route layout, server load
#               functions, form actions, page data, etc.  Run
#               `svelte-kit sync` after editing route structure
#               or modifying load function signatures to
#               regenerate the type definitions.  Often invoked
#               automatically by IDE tooling (svelte-language-
#               server runs it on file change), by `vite dev`
#               at startup, and by build scripts before
#               `svelte-check`.
#
# Author:  Svelte Team — Rich Harris (creator) + Ben McCann +
#          Conduitry + Tan Li Hau + many contributors.  Svelte
#          is the front-end framework that pioneered the compiler
#          approach to UI (compiles components to plain DOM
#          updates rather than shipping a virtual-DOM runtime).
#          SvelteKit is the official meta-framework for Svelte —
#          file-based routing, server-side rendering, form
#          actions, server load functions, adapter-based
#          deployment to Node/Vercel/Netlify/Cloudflare/static.
# Source:  https://github.com/sveltejs/kit
#          https://github.com/sveltejs/kit/blob/main/packages/kit/src/cli.js
# CLI:     packages/kit/svelte-kit.js (entrypoint) →
#          packages/kit/src/cli.js (the argv parser + dispatcher).
#          Uses `parseArgs` from `node:util` (Node 18.3+ stdlib).
# Library: node:util.parseArgs
#          ("Node.js stdlib argv parser" — added in Node 18.3.0
#           (June 2022) and stabilized in Node 22.  Provides a
#           ZERO-DEPENDENCY argv parsing function in the Node.js
#           standard library.  Returns a {values, positionals}
#           object from process.argv based on a declarative
#           options config with `type` ('string' | 'boolean'),
#           `short` (single-char alias), `default`, and
#           `multiple` (allow repeated flags as array).
#           Inspired by — and roughly compatible with — popular
#           userland parsers like `minimist` and `mri`, but
#           shipped INSIDE the Node runtime so projects can
#           depend on `node:util.parseArgs` without adding any
#           dependency to package.json.)
# License: MIT (svelte-kit); Node.js (MIT) for parseArgs
# Status:  svelte-kit — actively maintained as part of @sveltejs/kit
#          (20.5k+ stars, weekly npm downloads ~250k+);
#          parseArgs — STABILIZED in Node 22+ (December 2024);
#          experimental in Node 18 (June 2022) and Node 20.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — TS-NODE CROSSES TO 49
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents
# the 49TH TypeScript-Node CLI library variant.  TypeScript-Node climbs
# from 48 to 49 documented libraries (node:util.parseArgs via svelte-kit).
# New leaderboard: Rust=49, Go=49, TypeScript-Node=49 (THREE-WAY TIE AT 49
# RESTORED — the third three-way tie at 49-or-above of this round-
# sequence).  Taxonomy now spans 307 cross-language CLI library variants
# across 74 documented languages.
#
# Pattern: 1 new language (R565 Seed7) → R566 Rust=49 (color-eyre) →
# R567 Go=49 (kingpin) → R568 TS-Node=49 (parseArgs THIS).  This is
# the 3rd of 3 leader bumps in the current segment.  R569 expected
# to introduce a NEW LANGUAGE (75th).
#
# This completion EXPANDS Axis 1 (ARGV PARSING) within TS-Node.
# TS-Node now has DOCUMENTED Node argv parsers spanning:
#   - minimist (substack) — pre-existing
#   - mri (lukeed) — pre-existing
#   - meow (sindresorhus) — pre-existing
#   - yargs — pre-existing
#   - commander (TJ Holowaychuk) — pre-existing
#   - cac (egoist) — pre-existing
#   - sade (lukeed) — pre-existing
#   - arg (vercel) — pre-existing
#   - args (leo) — pre-existing
#   - oclif (Heroku) — pre-existing
#   - citty (unjs) — pre-existing
#   - gunshi (kazupon) — pre-existing
#   - clipanion (yarnpkg) — pre-existing
#   - cleye (privatenumber) — pre-existing
#   - gluegun (infinitered) — pre-existing
#   - stricli (Bloomberg) — pre-existing
#   - command-line-args (75lb) — R561 (Pyret)
#   - nopt (npm) — R564 (node-pre-gyp)
#   - node:util.parseArgs (Node stdlib) — R568, THIS
#
# parseArgs is DISTINCT from every other documented TS-Node argv parser
# by being SHIPPED INSIDE THE NODE.JS STDLIB itself — no userland
# dependency required.  This is the FIRST Node-stdlib-built-in argv
# parser to be documented in the taxonomy.  Compare:
#   * minimist: third-party, requires `npm install minimist`
#   * mri: third-party, requires `npm install mri`
#   * yargs: third-party, requires `npm install yargs`
#   * commander: third-party, requires `npm install commander`
#   * nopt: third-party (npm-inc), requires `npm install nopt`
#   * parseArgs: BUILT-IN, just `import { parseArgs } from 'node:util'`
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS node:util.parseArgs AND WHY IS IT THE 49TH TS-NODE CLI LIBRARY?
#
# node:util.parseArgs is **Node.js's standard-library argv parser** —
# the FIRST OFFICIAL ARGV PARSING UTILITY shipped with Node.js
# itself.  Added in Node 18.3.0 (June 2022) and stabilized in
# Node 22 (December 2024), parseArgs occupies a unique slot:
# every Node.js installation since 18.3 has a competent argv
# parser available with zero dependencies.
#
# parseArgs's distinguishing characteristics:
#
#   1. ZERO-DEPENDENCY STDLIB INCLUSION — `parseArgs` is part of
#      Node.js's `util` module.  Import it with:
#
#          import { parseArgs } from 'node:util';
#
#      No `npm install`, no `package.json` dependency, no
#      bundling concerns.  Available on every Node 18.3+
#      environment including Deno (via the node: compat layer),
#      Bun, and serverless runtimes (Cloudflare Workers, Vercel
#      Edge Functions where Node-compat is enabled).
#      Compare every other documented Node argv parser — all
#      require at least one userland dependency.  FIRST documented
#      argv parser shipped with the Node.js standard library.
#
#   2. DECLARATIVE OPTIONS CONFIG WITH STRING-TYPE-NAMES —
#      Where nopt uses JS constructors (R564) and yargs uses
#      builder chains, parseArgs uses a DECLARATIVE OPTIONS
#      CONFIG keyed by flag name with string-valued type names:
#
#          const { values, positionals } = parseArgs({
#              options: {
#                  version: { type: 'boolean', short: 'v' },
#                  help:    { type: 'boolean', short: 'h' },
#                  mode:    { type: 'string', default: 'development' },
#                  port:    { type: 'string', short: 'p' },
#                  watch:   { type: 'boolean', multiple: true },
#              },
#              allowPositionals: true,
#              strict: true
#          });
#
#      The two supported `type` values are `'string'` and
#      `'boolean'`.  Numbers, dates, URLs, and other types are
#      handled by the caller AFTER parsing (parseArgs returns
#      string values; the user calls `Number(values.port)` or
#      `new URL(values.target)`).  Compare:
#         * minimist: untyped (everything is a string-or-array)
#         * mri: untyped
#         * yargs: chainable type methods (.number()/.boolean())
#         * commander: chainable option parsers
#         * nopt: JS-constructor-as-type (Boolean, Number, Date,
#                  url, path) — six types built-in
#         * parseArgs: TWO types ('string', 'boolean') —
#                       intentionally minimal; caller handles the
#                       rest
#      FIRST documented Node argv parser with intentionally
#      minimal two-type-only config (vs builder type methods /
#      vs JS constructors / vs untyped).
#
#   3. RETURNS {values, positionals} TWO-OBJECT RESULT — Where
#      most parsers return a single argv object with a special
#      `_` key for positionals (minimist's `argv._`), parseArgs
#      returns a DISTINCT TWO-OBJECT result:
#
#          {
#              values: { mode: 'development', help: false },
#              positionals: ['sync']
#          }
#
#      The `values` object is keyed by flag name with parsed
#      values; the `positionals` array holds non-flag arguments
#      in order.  Compare:
#         * minimist: `{_: [], ...flags}` — positionals on `_`
#         * mri: same as minimist
#         * yargs: `{_: [], $0: 'progname', ...flags}`
#         * commander: `program.args` for positionals
#         * nopt: `argv.remain` for positionals
#         * parseArgs: SEPARATE `positionals` array — cleaner
#                       schema, no special `_` key
#      FIRST documented Node argv parser with cleanly-separated
#      values/positionals result object (vs underscore-key).
#
#   4. STRICT MODE BY DEFAULT — parseArgs's `strict: true`
#      option (which is the recommended default) makes the
#      parser THROW on unknown flags rather than silently
#      collecting them.  This catches typos at parse time.
#      Compare:
#         * minimist: silent — unknown flags appear in result
#         * mri: silent
#         * yargs: configurable via `.strict()` builder method
#         * commander: configurable
#         * nopt: silent — unknowns appear in `argv.original`
#         * parseArgs: explicit `strict` parameter, recommended
#                       on
#      FIRST documented Node argv parser with explicit-strict-
#      mode-as-recommended-default semantics.
#
#   5. ECOSYSTEM-WIDE ADOPTION FOR ZERO-DEPENDENCY MODERN TOOLS —
#      parseArgs is the choice of modern post-2022 Node tools
#      that aim for ZERO RUNTIME DEPENDENCIES.  Major users:
#         * @sveltejs/kit (THIS — SvelteKit's `svelte-kit` binary)
#         * @sveltejs/cli (`sv` binary)
#         * pkg-pr-new (StackBlitz continuous releases)
#         * corepack (Node's package-manager-manager,
#                      shipped with Node 16+)
#         * various TypeScript-Node tools opting for stdlib
#         * Internal Node.js tooling
#      Compare:
#         * minimist: 250B downloads/week, but third-party dep
#         * yargs: 50M downloads/week, third-party
#         * nopt: npm internal, third-party
#         * parseArgs: NO DOWNLOAD COUNT — comes with Node
#      FIRST documented Node argv parser with zero-download-
#      count provenance (because it's built into Node itself).
#
# parseArgs's relationship to other documented TS-Node CLI libraries:
#
#   * Like minimist — minimal argv parser, returns plain object
#   * Unlike minimist — separates positionals from values; uses
#                        declarative options config with types
#   * Like mri — minimal, fast
#   * Unlike mri — typed (string/boolean) vs untyped
#   * Like nopt — declarative options config
#   * Unlike nopt — strings-as-types vs constructors-as-types;
#                    ships with Node vs external dependency
#   * Closest cross-language analogs:
#         * Go: Go stdlib `flag` package (also ships with the
#                runtime, also offers minimal type set
#                StringVar/IntVar/BoolVar, also recommended for
#                "small CLIs" before reaching for cobra/urfave)
#         * Rust: no clear stdlib analog (Rust stdlib has no
#                  argv parser; clap/structopt/argh are all
#                  third-party)
#     parseArgs is the FIRST documented stdlib-bundled argv
#     parser for the TypeScript-Node language slot.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# THE svelte-kit CLI — parseArgs + kleur for error coloring
#
# svelte-kit's argv parsing is direct parseArgs from node:util:
#
#     import { parseArgs } from 'node:util';
#     import colors from 'kleur';
#
#     const help = `
#       Usage: svelte-kit <command> [options]
#
#       Commands:
#         sync        Synchronise generated type definitions
#
#       Options:
#         --version, -v   Show version number
#         --help, -h      Show this help message
#
#       Sync Options:
#         --mode <mode>   Specify a mode for loading environment
#                          variables (default: development)
#     `;
#
#     let parsed;
#     try {
#         parsed = parseArgs({
#             options: {
#                 version: { type: 'boolean', short: 'v' },
#                 help:    { type: 'boolean', short: 'h' },
#                 mode:    { type: 'string', default: 'development' }
#             },
#             allowPositionals: true,
#             strict: true
#         });
#     } catch (err) {
#         console.error(colors.bold().red(`> ${err.message}`));
#         console.log(help);
#         process.exit(1);
#     }
#
#     const { values, positionals } = parsed;
#
#     if (values.version) { console.log(pkg.version); process.exit(0); }
#     if (values.help)    { console.log(help);        process.exit(0); }
#
#     const command = positionals[0];
#     if (command === 'sync') {
#         // ... run sync ...
#     }
#
# Subcommand: `sync` — synchronise generated type definitions
# (re-generate `.svelte-kit/types/` from route layout, load
# functions, form actions, etc).
#
# Five-axis distinctness from every other documented Node argv parser:
#
#   1. ZERO-DEPENDENCY STDLIB INCLUSION — Every other documented
#      Node argv parser requires `npm install <pkg>`.  parseArgs
#      ships with Node itself (since 18.3, stable in 22+).
#      FIRST documented Node argv parser bundled with the
#      runtime.
#
#   2. TWO-TYPE MINIMAL CONFIG — Every other documented Node
#      argv parser supports many types (4-10) via builders,
#      constructors, or struct fields.  parseArgs supports
#      exactly TWO types ('string', 'boolean') — caller handles
#      conversion.  FIRST documented Node argv parser with
#      intentionally-minimal two-type-only config.
#
#   3. {values, positionals} CLEAN RESULT — Every other documented
#      Node argv parser returns positionals via a special `_`
#      key, or via a separate `args` property on the program
#      object.  parseArgs returns positionals as a SEPARATE
#      ARRAY in the result object.  FIRST documented Node argv
#      parser with this clean schema.
#
#   4. STRICT-MODE-AS-PARAMETER — Every other documented Node
#      argv parser either silently accepts unknowns (minimist/
#      mri) or makes strict mode opt-in via a builder method
#      (.strict() in yargs).  parseArgs exposes strict mode as
#      an explicit constructor parameter that's recommended-on.
#      FIRST documented Node argv parser with this explicit
#      strict-mode parameter.
#
#   5. NODE-VERSION-FEATURE PROVENANCE — Every other documented
#      Node argv parser is versioned independently from Node
#      itself (yargs v17, minimist v1.2.x, etc).  parseArgs is
#      versioned WITH NODE — its features track Node releases
#      (added 18.3, stabilized in 22, multiple-flag-as-array
#      added in 20.x).  Library version IS the Node version.
#      FIRST documented Node argv parser with this Node-version-
#      tied versioning model.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# COMMAND-LINE OPTIONS (sourced directly from
# https://github.com/sveltejs/kit/blob/main/packages/kit/src/cli.js
# parseArgs options definition and help text.)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
typeset -A opt_args

local -a _sk_cmds
_sk_cmds=(
    'sync:synchronise generated type definitions in .svelte-kit/types/'
)

_arguments -C \
    '(- *)'{-v,--version}'[show version number]' \
    '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help message]' \
    '1: :->cmd' \
    '*::arg:->args' \
    && ret=0

case $state in
    cmd)
        _describe -t commands 'svelte-kit command' _sk_cmds && ret=0
        ;;
    args)
        case $words[1] in
            sync)
                _arguments -s \
                    '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
                    '--mode=[mode for loading environment variables (default: development)]:mode:(development production preview test staging)' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
        esac
        ;;
esac

return ret
